Airtel on Vodafone-Idea merger deal: Consolidation of India‚Äôs telecom industry should not be forced by unfair means
===================================================================================================================

Britain's Vodafone Group on Monday confirmed it is in discussion to merge with Idea Cellular in an all-share deal to create the country's largest telecom operator with 43 per cent revenue marketshare.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

By: [PTI](https://indianexpress.com/agency/pti/)   
New Delhi | January 31, 2017 18:50 IST

![Image 7: Newsguard](https://indianexpress.com/wp-content/themes/indianexpress/images/icon-newsguard.svg)

![Image 8: clock_logo](https://indianexpress.com/wp-content/themes/indianexpress/images/icons/clock.svg) 3 min read

*   _![Image 9: facebook](https://indianexpress.com/wp-content/themes/indianexpress/images/icon-fb.svg)_
*   _![Image 10: twitter](https://indianexpress.com/wp-content/themes/indianexpress/images/x-story.svg)_
*   _![Image 11: whatsapp](https://indianexpress.com/wp-content/themes/indianexpress/images/icon-whatsapp.svg)_
*   _![Image 12: Reddit](https://indianexpress.com/wp-content/themes/indianexpress/images/black-icon-reddit.svg)_

 ![Image 13:  Vodafone and Idea Cellular, Bharti Airtel, India Mobile network Industry, India Mobile Network industry consolidation, India news, National news, India news, National news](https://indianexpress.com/wp-content/themes/indianexpress/images/default-ie.jpg) Airtel has challenged clean chit given by the Telecom Regulatory Authority of India for allowing Reliance Jio to provide free telecom services.While welcoming the merger talks between Vodafone and Idea Cellular, Bharti Airtel in a veiled attack on telecom regulator said that consolidation should not be an outcome of a forced situation created by extending favours to a particular company. ‚ÄúWe welcome the news of the proposed alliance between Vodafone and Idea Cellular‚Ä¶However, it is important to ensure that such consolidations are not an outcome of a forced situation created by offering an ‚Äòunfair playing field‚Äô to any particular company while completely destroying the viability of the others,‚Äù Bharti Airtel (India and South Asia) MD and CEO Gopal Vittal said in a statement.

**Watch What Else is Making News**

![Image 14](https://indianexpress.com/wp-content/themes/indianexpress/images/default-ie.jpg)Britain‚Äôs Vodafone Group on Monday confirmed it is in discussion to merge its Indian unit with Idea Cellular in an all-share deal to create the country‚Äôs largest telecom operator with 43 per cent revenue marketshare.

Advertisement

The combined entity will pose formidable competition to the current market leader Airtel and aggressive new entrant Reliance Jio.

Vittal said that consolidation due to forced situation would be an unfavourable situation, which is not only bad for the sector, customers and the employees, but will also adversely impact the overall investment climate and above all revenues to government.

Airtel has challenged clean chit given by the Telecom Regulatory Authority of India for allowing Reliance Jio to provide free telecom services.

In its 25-page petition before the Telecom Disputes Settlement and Appellate Tribunal (TDSAT), Airtel had asked the quasi-judicial body to direct Trai to ensure Jio does not provide its free voice and data plan beyond December 3.

Advertisement

In the petition, Airtel had alleged that Trai in its decision dated October 20 ‚Äúerroneously‚Äù concluded that since Jio‚Äôs promotional offer of free services was only valid till December 3, it is consistent with the direction for 90 days.

The case is scheduled for hearing at TDSAT on Wednesday.

On proposed merger of Vodafone and Idea , Vittal said that the consolidation is always good, especially for any capital intensive sector with multiple players.

‚ÄúA few solid and profitable players are always better for an industry, as they can make substantial investments and offer quality products and services to customers in a sustainable fashion,‚Äù Vittal said.

 

